\begin_layout Paragraph
Advertisement on Internet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the past, the most efficient way to deliver a message was to emit it
 to the biggest possible public.
 From now on, advertisers will have an increasing ability to reach specific
 audiences.
 The usage of tracking, customer profiling and the growing popularity of
 niche content gives a a number of more specific and smaller market target.
 However this advertisement is more segmented but much better defined ands
 so it's much more efficient.
 With an agreement with a specialist blog writer in a a specific domain,
 advertisers are able to communicate through famous specialists delivering
 interesting and specialized advices including marketed products to passionates.
 With this scenario, the message communicated by the brand, usually delivered
 in a top-down topology on television ( communication from the top of the
 head of the country communicator , like TV, to the mass) , is now certified
 as a good advice by a specialist of the area.
 The impact of the message would much more better on internet than with
 television.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among others, Comcast Spotlight is one such advertiser employing this method
 in their video on demand menus.
 These advertisements are targeted to a specific group and can be viewed
 by anyone wishing to find out more about a particular business or practice,
 from their home.
 This causes the viewer to become proactive and actually choose what advertiseme
nts they want to view.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Google AdSense is an example of niche marketing.
 Google calculates the primary purpose of a website and adjusts ads accordingly;
 it uses key words on the page (or even in emails) to find the general ideas
 of topics disused and places ads that will most likely be clicked on by
 viewers of the email account or website visitors.
 Also preferences of the Internet user are taking into account with the
 use of little files (so called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cookies
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) that collect data on the user browsing habits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Advertisement Influence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The advertisement generates money for the content providers.
 Speaking about video, the advertisement mainly support the hosting service.Somet
imes, like on Youtube, the money generated partly goes to the creators to
 motivate them creating content.
 On such platforms, the advertisement is necessary to sustain the service
 provided.
 However, according to some researches , it appears that the advertisement
 could detrimental influence on people that are watching it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most important element of advertising is not information but suggestion
 – more or less making use of associations, emotions and drives in the subconsci
ous, such as sex drive, herd instinct, desires such as happiness, appearance,
 self-esteem, social status and fears such as illness, weaknesses, loneliness,
 etc..
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-4"

\end_inset

 Cause-related marketing in which advertisers link their product to some
 worthy social cause has boomed over the past decade.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Advertising uses the model role of celebrities or popular figures and makes
 deliberate use of humor as well as of associations with color, tunes, certain
 names and terms.
 These are factors of how one perceives himself and one's self-worth.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-5"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The efficiency of advertising is improved through advertising research.
 Universities, of course supported by business and in co-operation with
 other disciplines (s.
 above), mainly Psychiatry, Anthropology, Neurology and behavioral sciences,
 are constantly in search for ever more refined, sophisticated, subtle and
 crafty methods to make advertising more effective.
 "NeuroMarketing is a controversial new field of marketing which uses medical
 technologies such as functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging (fMRI)—not to
 heal, but to sell products.
 Advertising and marketing firms have long used the insights and research
 methods of psychology in order to sell products, of course.
 But today these practices are reaching epidemic levels, and with a complicity
 on the part of the psychological profession that exceeds that of the past.
 The result is an enormous advertising and marketing onslaught that comprises,
 arguably, the largest single psychological project ever undertaken.
 Yet, this great undertaking remains largely ignored by the American Psychologic
al Association."
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-13"

\end_inset

 Robert McChesney calls it "the greatest concerted attempt at psychological
 manipulation in all of human history."
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-14"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following are examples to show the effects of advertisements on children
 and teenagers and how these lead them to problems .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
obesity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The television advertising is accused of contributing to the increase of
 the obesity epidemic in developed countries.
 A report submitted in 2003 to the Food Standards Agency in the UK that
 advertising for food has an effect on children by affecting the food preference
 and purchase applications for malsains products 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-15"

\end_inset

.
 A group of French scientists nutrition issues officials claimed in 2008,
 in an article entitled "fatten the children to save the television" ( «
 Engraisser les enfants pour sauver la télévision ») , and referring to
 "recent reports": "There is even a link between high exposure the TV ads
 and obesity in children aged 2 to 11 years and adolescents aged 12 to 18
 years.
 Exposure to television advertising on high energy density foods (including
 sweet and fat) is associated with a higher prevalence of obesity.
 ".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2010 the World Health Organization drove the point home: "television
 advertising influences the food preferences of children and their purchase
 requests and consumption patterns" [62].
 At the same time, in France, What to choose noted that 80% of advertising
 to children was for food, and that 80% of them were too fat or too sucrés63.
 This study was critical to the food industry's commitments in 2008 under
 the aegis of the ANIA, to reduce advertising to enfants [64].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
tobacco
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Smoking in films affects teenagers: a teenager sees movies with smoking,
 the more likely to smoke.
 The reverse is also true, namely that few teenagers smoking among those
 who are not subject to tabagiques [65 ]films.
 The World Health Organization recalls Article 13 of the Framework Convention
 on Tobacco and calls for measures to limit the presence of tobacco in films[66].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Americans Chomsky and Herman, in their criticism of the functioning of the
 media in democracy theorized a propaganda model "regulation by advertising"
 is one of five filters.
 For reasons of financial and economic survival, the private media are primarily
 concerned with good selling potential audience to advertisers that the
 "subsidizing"; gold they are, according to these authors, "more usually
 worn to avoid overly complicated programs or affecting disturbing controversies
 that might reduce the" brain time available "public" 67.
